Prolog
"Please, my lord!" pleaded Queen Eirwen, "do not send her away! She is still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought, his gaze darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl in the eyes of the Ice King meant weakness. After all, he had until now only sired sons.
"You have two options: either you kill the child or you send her into the wilderness. That is his punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Earlier, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, while in the South was a kingdom full of magical powers. But the North showed its greed, and there was an endless war between the two kingdoms until the South finally offered a truce.
The desperation in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she should bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a single kingdom. The North accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"Please, my king, do with me as you will, imprison me, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen with utter loathing. Perhaps, but only perhaps, would he show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his darkest hours and who had given him his sons.
"Very well. The child can stay in the palace," he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the floor. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter into one of Eirwen's free rooms. Then he commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the execution square, where all the citizens of the city could witness it.
While the guards escorted her to the execution square, a loud uproar broke out among the citizens as they realized their only, beloved queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Again, others questioned why this should happen, but all were in agreement.
"Let her go!"
"Why is this being done to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman, who had just been a queen, was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the most terrible thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Never give up, Kari." This marked the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace
Only a single knock was heard from the room located farthest to the left in the perpetually cold palace's southern wing. The servants who passed by wondered what was inside the room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors among the maidservants spread. It was said that the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room and was waiting to be let out.
Her assumption could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory, and walked toward the southern wing, while the servants wandered around and whispered to each other. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
The rumors naturally also concerned Ivory, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" whispered Ivory before the intricately decorated door, adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered whether—unlike the last attempt—actual entry would be granted. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book at Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock was heard from inside, probably to say that she was there. Where else would she be?
"May I enter?" asked Ivory. Earlier, Ivory would have walked in without asking.
From inside, Ivory heard a knock. That probably meant a "Yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound from a room supposedly left empty, although Ivory had been entering there for several years.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for her. Everywhere there was paper. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and little or no light. In addition, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a blizzard had swept through.
The girl lay curled in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and was reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit the room.
"Which notebook is this?" asked Ivory and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
